title: C++ API: Missing features in comparison to C API

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

labels.name: contributions welcome
labels.description: lower priority issues for the core ORT teams

body:
I am currently working on another project that makes use of the `C++` API via `onnxruntime/include/onnxruntime/core/session`.

When comparing the `C++` API to the `C` API, I have found several `C` features that are not exposed in `C++`. For example:

- `SequenceTypeInfo`, `GetSequenceTypeInfo`, `GetSequenceElementType`
- `MapTypeInfo`, `GetMapTypeInfo`, `GetMapKeyType`, `GetMapValueType`

In a private fork, I made these available by changing the `onnxruntime_cxx_api.h` and `onnxruntime_cxx_inline.h`.

Are there plans to make everything available in the `C++` API? Am I missing an obvious reason as to why they are not supported?

**System information**

- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): custom build (master, currently based on 40d80cde8)

**Describe alternatives you've considered**

I could continue maintaining these changes in my local fork - I'd rather not.

If you want me to, I could open a pull request with some of the mentioned functions in the `C++` API.

title: Support override of free dimensions by name
body:
This enables sizes of free dimensions to be specified by name while a session is created, in addition to denotation.  

The existing API which is based on denotation is preserved with binary compatibility (though renamed to AddFreeDimensionOverride*ByDenotation*) and is still used by Winml.   A new API named AddFreeDimensionOverride*ByName*) is added.

The new API enables models which contain free width and height dimensions, for example, to be fully optimized during creation of the session.

title: Flush and trim resources in DML EP in OnSessionInitializationEnd API
body:
This adds an EP method OnSessionInitializationEnd, similar to OnRunEnd.  The DML EP uses this method to sync and trim resources used to upload weights.

Previously Winml would do this itself, and so memory usage was higher when using ORT APIs.  Winml had already switched earlier from doing this step after first evaluation to doing it at the end of session initialization, to make first evaluation faster.  However that change was lost during some of the re-layering work, so this change restores the desired behavior for Winml as well.

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.

Both onnxruntime and tensorflow are built with DNNL
```python
import os
import time

os.environ["CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES"] = "-1"
os.environ['TF_KERAS'] = '1'
os.environ["OMP_NUM_THREADS"] = "1"

import numpy as np
import onnxmltools
import onnxruntime as ort
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras import Input, Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import (Activation, BatchNormalization, Conv1D,
                                     Dense, MaxPooling1D, add, concatenate)

tf.config.threading.set_inter_op_parallelism_threads(1)
tf.config.threading.set_intra_op_parallelism_threads(1)

def Inception(filters,
            kernel_size,
            pool_size,
            padding='same',
            use_batch_norm=False):
    def inception_module(i):
        kernel_sizes = [kernel_size * (2 ** i) for i in range(3)]
        pool_i = MaxPooling1D(pool_size=3, strides=1, padding=padding)(i)
        conv_list = [Conv1D(filters // 4, 1, padding=padding, use_bias=False)(pool_i)]
        for ks in kernel_sizes:
            o = Conv1D(filters // 4, ks, padding=padding, use_bias=False)(i)
            conv_list.append(o)
        o = concatenate(conv_list)
        if use_batch_norm:
            o = BatchNormalization()(o)
        o = Activation('relu')(o)
        o = MaxPooling1D(pool_size, strides=1, padding='same')(o)
        return o

    def inception(i):
        o = inception_module(i)
        o = inception_module(o)
        o = inception_module(o)
        i = Conv1D(int(o.shape[-1]), 1, padding=padding, use_bias=False)(i)
        if use_batch_norm:
            i = BatchNormalization()(i)
        o = add([i, o])
        o = Activation('relu')(o)
        return o
    return inception

F, N, T = 30, 32, 4096
x = np.random.randn(N, T, F).astype('float32')
y = np.random.randn(N, T, 1).astype('float32')

filters_list = [128, 128]

for pool_size in [3, 32, 64, 128]:
    print('---------------------')
    print('pool_size', pool_size)
    print('---------------------')
    o = i = Input((T, F))
    for filters in filters_list:
        o = Inception(filters, 3, pool_size=pool_size)(o)
    o = Conv1D(1, 1, padding='same')(o)
    model = Model(inputs=[i], outputs=[o])
    model.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='sgd')

    model.save('model.h5')
    onnx_model = onnxmltools.convert_keras(model)
    onnxmltools.utils.save_model(onnx_model, 'model.onnx')

    model(x, training=False)
    ti = time.time()
    model(x, training=False)
    print('keras time: ', time.time() - ti)

    so = ort.SessionOptions()
    so.intra_op_num_threads = 1
    so.inter_op_num_threads = 1
    sess = ort.InferenceSession("model.onnx", so)
    for provider in sess.get_providers()[:1]:
        sess.set_providers([provider])
        input_name = sess.get_inputs()[0].name
        sess.run(None, {input_name: x})[0]
        ti = time.time()
        sess.run(None, {input_name: x})[0]
        print('onnx-' + provider, 'time: ', time.time() - ti)
```

**Expected behavior**
onnxruntime should be at least as fast as keras

title: Dropout kernel and function body expansion updates.

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
The change addresses two issues:

- **Function body**
  - This change enables the handling of function bodies that require function proto context in ORT by creating function body at Node Verification stage.
  - Fixes bugs around function body expansion that were causing segmentation faults and index out of bound exceptions.
  - Adds tests for NegativeLikelihoodLoss forward kernel (defined by function). 

- **Dropout-12 kernel**
  - Pursuant to https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/2725 this PR introduces `training_mode` input to Dropout-12 kernel to repurpose this kernel for both inferencing and training without breaking the existing inferencing behavior where default probability is zero. The motivation for the change was to change the spec's default probability to 0.5 to make it inline with PyTorch, TensorFlow and ONNX Runtime Training.
  - Updates ORT-ONNX test infrastructure to handle dropout tests by counting the number of zeros in the output as opposed to doing absolute comparisions which will _almost_ never match because mask generated by ORT will be different from that of ONNX model baseline (generated by python based reference implementation that use np.random distribution) 
  - Separates out TrainableDropout because existing models using it will pass `training_mode` input and instead will expect it to be used for training directly. 


Please note CI builds are failing due to below tests not passing but I believe these failures are **not** related to my change, please review with confidence:

- ParallelExecutor.TestStatusPropagation
- ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTests/ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTest.TestNullInterOpThreadPool/0, where GetParam() = 1
- ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTests/ParallelExecutorThreadPoolTest.TestNullInterOpThreadPool/1, where GetParam() = 0

title: Fork WinML IDL Guids
body:
Issue: WinML interfaces share the same guids as the inbox distribution of WinML.
Sharing these guids cause the component to fail WACK compliance, as Inbox SDK component IDs cannot be reused by out-of-the-box components.

To support the component in Store apps in the future, we do not want to change the guids, and introduce a possible breaking change to client apps.

Fix: Fork the GUIDs that define the WinML interfaces to be unique across the Microsoft and Windows namespaces.

title: Convert Gelu to use TryParallelFor
E2E_example_model for quantization expects NHWC, not NCHW format?

labels.name: quantization
labels.description: issues related to quantization

body:
**Describe the bug**
The model at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/E2E_example_model/resnet50_v1.onnx seems to use NHWC format for its input (being exported from tensorflow), and hence doesn't seem to work with the default calibration tool as supplied which preprocesses images to be in NCHW format.

This should probably be replaced with a model that expects its inputs in NCHW format, as can be found at https://zenodo.org/record/2592612

Alternatively, for performance it might be better to use a model exported from pytorch or caffe, since I believe tensorflow only works with NHWC format internally and inserts transposes to get to NHWC format (there's a version exported from caffe2 here: https://github.com/onnx/models/tree/master/vision/classification/resnet/resnet50)

title: Improve TopK performance.
body:
**Description**: 
 Update TopK implementation
  - add faster heap implementation from Xavier
    - significantly faster than using std::priority_queue
  - special case k=1
  - update selector for when to use heap and when to use nth_element based on performance testing
  - parallelize if enough work to do
  - reduce templatized code
  - add some extra unit tests.

Average speedup is 3.75x using these combinations of inputs:

```
    batches = [10, 25, 50]
    batch_size = [8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512, 1024, 2048]
    k = [1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 128]
```

For larger inputs (e.g. 50x2048 with k=4) the speedup is over 20x.

**Motivation and Context**
Address performance gap with SKL.
